WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.970
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today, we're&nbsp;
going to expand matrix theory in a bold new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:21.090
direction using this new framework for negative&nbsp;
numbers and integers that we've been developing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.650 --> 00:00:29.460
We now have control of integers, so we can&nbsp;
use those integers to populate pixels, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:36.360
then the pixels populate maxwells. Maxwells are a&nbsp;
replacement for matrices; they are an extension of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:43.230
the idea of the matrix. We're going to introduce&nbsp;
a new type of object represented by this "max&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:49.590
bracket int," which is a maxwell from integers.&nbsp;
Let me explain what kind of object this is.

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:55.830
Here's an example of it. Here's a maxwell from&nbsp;
integers, and you may recognize that inside it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.830 --> 00:01:03.390
there are pixels, a pixel being a list of two&nbsp;
numbers. But in this case, the numbers that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:12.618
are involved are integers: -1, -1, 0, 0, 0, 1,&nbsp;
1, -1, 0, and so on. We have repetitions, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.618 --> 00:01:20.370
is alright because we have an M-set: 1, -1, 1, -1,&nbsp;
1, 2. And of course, the order doesn't matter. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.370 --> 00:01:29.460
this is an M-set or multiset of pixels, and a&nbsp;
pixel now is allowed to have integer entries.

00:01:31.170 --> 00:01:36.780
We're going to be able to represent this&nbsp;
kind of thing in a new fashion using a screen&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:45.960
representation that extends in all directions&nbsp;
in the plane—a very novel kind of thing. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.960 --> 00:01:52.770
have a look at this representation here.&nbsp;
How does this thing represent that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.770 --> 00:01:59.940
first of all, you see these four lines forming&nbsp;
this cross on the page, signifying this special&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.940 --> 00:02:06.180
point here or the special position. This is&nbsp;
the position that corresponds to (0, 0). So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.180 --> 00:02:14.550
this is the origin in this screen representation&nbsp;
of pixels. This is the (0, 0) position,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:21.330
and there are actually a couple of (0,&nbsp;
0) pixels in our multiset, so we count&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.330 --> 00:02:27.390
the multiplicity and put a "2" there. That "2"&nbsp;
represents the number of pixels of the form (0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:35.160
0). This "1" here represents the&nbsp;
number of pixels of the form (0, 1).

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:39.630
Okay, so this is the (0, 0) position, this is&nbsp;
the (0, 1) position, this is the (0, 2) position,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.630 --> 00:02:48.570
this is the (1, 0) position, then the (1, 1),&nbsp;
(1, 2). We're claiming that there is one (0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.570 --> 00:02:56.130
1) somewhere, and there it is right there. And&nbsp;
what about this one here? That represents the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.130 --> 00:03:06.480
position (-1, -1). Alright, so this "1" means that&nbsp;
there is a single (-1, -1), and there it is right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:15.690
there. In addition, we have three things of the&nbsp;
form (1, -1): (1, -1), (1, -1), (1, -1)—there are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:21.960
three of them. And also one over here—that's&nbsp;
in the position (1, 2)—that's that one there.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:27.660
So, this is a record, like a multiplicity&nbsp;
list, of the various pixels that appear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:34.380
in this maxwell. The novelty is that our&nbsp;
indices are now allowed to be integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:44.220
not starting from 1, not starting from 0 either,&nbsp;
but integers. So, if we were just starting with 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:49.470
then we would really be talking about the&nbsp;
screen that extends below to the right here. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.470 --> 00:03:54.930
this would be the (1, 1) entry: (1, 1),&nbsp;
(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3). So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.930 --> 00:04:02.550
here's sort of standard matrix theory, if&nbsp;
you like, there. And then extending to zeros,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:09.660
allowing 0 as an index, we would have this larger&nbsp;
screen that includes this border. But now, today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.660 --> 00:04:14.340
we're going further, and we're allowing&nbsp;
integers, including negative numbers, in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:21.420
vertical direction and also in the horizontal&nbsp;
direction—these are maxwells from integers.

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:27.120
Okay, so let's make the official definitions.&nbsp;
We're working in this context where we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:31.590
integers consisting of both natural numbers&nbsp;
and negative numbers. Here are some examples&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.590 --> 00:04:35.520
of integers: there is the integer that&nbsp;
we would normally call 5—it's actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:40.890
a natural number. Here's the integer that&nbsp;
we normally call -3—it's a negative number.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:40.890 --> 00:04:49.080
Here's our empty set or empty multiset, which&nbsp;
is the zero number. Okay, so we're not going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:54.570
to always use our marks and anti-marks to&nbsp;
construct numbers because then our M-sets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.570 --> 00:05:01.680
that we're illustrating would end up looking&nbsp;
very hard and complicated for us. A computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:05.760
wouldn't necessarily have any problem dealing&nbsp;
with these kinds of things, but we prefer to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:12.420
deal with our ordinary Hindu-Arabic numerals.&nbsp;
But we're going to always consider these to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:16.650
be just replacements for the fundamental&nbsp;
objects, which are integers of this form.

00:05:16.650 --> 00:05:23.340
And then the definition is that a pixel from&nbsp;
integers is now a two-list from int. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:32.400
a pixel from integers is a two-list from int,&nbsp;
and here is the type of pixel from integer. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:38.820
for example, this thing here is a list because&nbsp;
it has two elements with a comma there—the first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:44.940
element is an integer, the second element&nbsp;
is also an integer. We would more routinely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.940 --> 00:05:54.000
write this in the shorter form as the list&nbsp;
(4, -1). Here's an anti-mark in that M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:59.040
which means it's actually -1. So,&nbsp;
this is a pixel from integers.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:07.890
And then a maxwell from integers is an M-set of&nbsp;
these pixels from integers, and the type is max&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.890 --> 00:06:15.030
int. So, for example, here is a maxwell from&nbsp;
integers—it's a multiset consisting of a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.030 --> 00:06:22.740
of pixels, and the pixels are from integers. You&nbsp;
can see they have integer entries, and there are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:30.570
two lists—they each have a pair of entries. So now&nbsp;
it's natural for us to extend our representation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.570 --> 00:06:38.020
of maxwells from what we formerly considered in&nbsp;
terms of natural numbers to these integers as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.020 --> 00:06:45.550
indices. For that, we move to the integer screen,&nbsp;
which is basically the entire page extending in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.550 --> 00:06:52.150
all directions. Prominently, we have these four&nbsp;
lines represented by these two vertical ones and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:57.280
these two horizontal ones that will sort of&nbsp;
frame this screen and tell us where we are.

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:04.810
Okay, so let's make sure that we know where the&nbsp;
labels all fit. Each one of these little boxes is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:11.620
the home of a pixel from integers. Prominently,&nbsp;
the first one and the most important is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:21.400
origin of this picture, the (0, 0) pixel—it's&nbsp;
right in the middle of these four lines. Then,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:28.810
as we go down, the first coordinate increases,&nbsp;
just like for ordinary matrices: (0, 0), (1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.810 --> 00:07:37.570
0), (2, 0). Correspondingly, if we go up, we&nbsp;
decrease to become negative-valued: (-1, 0), (-2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:44.470
0), (-3, 0), and so on. If we move to the right,&nbsp;
then the second entry increases, so we go (0, 1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.470 --> 00:07:51.160
(0, 2), (0, 3), and so on. And if we move to the&nbsp;
left, then it becomes (0, -1), (0, -2), and so on.

00:07:52.930 --> 00:07:58.225
Down here, we have (1, 1), (1, 2),&nbsp;
(1, 3), (2, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.225 --> 00:08:03.370
(3, 1), (3, 2), (3, 3), and so on. So here is&nbsp;
the sort of more familiar framework for matrices,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:13.960
and now we're extending everything to the integer&nbsp;
domain. Note that we've made some special markings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:20.680
here for the diagonal elements: (0, 0), (1, 1),&nbsp;
(2, 2), (3, 3), along with the negative ones:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:27.460
(-1, -1), (-2, -2), and so on. They&nbsp;
play a particularly important role. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.460 --> 00:08:33.610
this diagonal is distinguished by going&nbsp;
through our distinguished central square.

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:42.700
This is now the new framework for linear&nbsp;
algebra, okay? It's a 21st-century framework&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.700 --> 00:08:50.650
for linear algebra, encompassing familiar matrix&nbsp;
theory but also extending it in a very important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.650 --> 00:08:58.840
new direction. And so now, of course, we can&nbsp;
represent a maxwell on our new screen just by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:04.600
recording the various multiplicities of the pixels&nbsp;
that occur. So let's have a look at this example.

00:09:05.140 --> 00:09:11.050
Here is a maxwell—it's a multiset of pixels&nbsp;
from integers, and we want to record how many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.050 --> 00:09:17.260
pixels there are in this multiset of different&nbsp;
kinds. So, we might start with this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:22.210
the first one that's pictured, although remember&nbsp;
this thing is unordered, so it's not necessarily&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:29.380
the case that things are organized in a coherent&nbsp;
way here. But here we see the pixel (-2, -1). Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:36.010
where is that going to be? Well, here is (0,&nbsp;
0). If we go up in the vertical direction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.010 --> 00:09:43.930
we are decreasing the first entry—so vertical is&nbsp;
the first entry here. So there's 0, there's -1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:49.360
there's -2. And then if we want to go -1 in&nbsp;
the horizontal direction, it means we're over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:55.840
here. So this pixel is represented by this&nbsp;
little portion of the screen, and how many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.840 --> 00:10:02.890
of them are there? There are 2. So there are&nbsp;
two of them, so I'm taking care of those two.

00:10:02.890 --> 00:10:11.770
How about (-1, 2)? Well, that would be -1 in&nbsp;
the vertical direction and 2 in the horizontal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:11.770 --> 00:10:21.550
direction, so we're over here. And how many of&nbsp;
those are there? Just the one. How about (0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:28.750
-1)? So, 0 in that direction, -1 in the&nbsp;
horizontal direction—that's right there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:28.750 --> 00:10:39.910
and there are one, two, three of them. (1, 1) is&nbsp;
one of them, (2, -1), so that's two down and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:51.730
one across—there are four of them. And (0, 3):&nbsp;
(0, 0), (0, 1), (0, 2), (0, 3)—is one of them.

00:10:54.100 --> 00:11:00.400
To make this maybe more readable, I could fill&nbsp;
in the rest with some zeros to structure the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:06.310
thing a bit more clearly, give it some more shape,&nbsp;
although strictly speaking, I don't really need to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.310 --> 00:11:12.250
do this because I'm just recording which pixels&nbsp;
are there, and there's no obligation for me to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.250 --> 00:11:17.860
record everything in a nice little rectangular&nbsp;
array. I can do so if I like, but I don't have to.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:17.860 --> 00:11:24.970
So that would be one reasonable representation,&nbsp;
if I've done it correctly, of this maxwell, M.

00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:35.680
Now, over here, I want to also indicate the&nbsp;
support of this maxwell. So, the support of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:44.950
maxwell is a set of pixels—the set of pixels&nbsp;
that actually occur in the maxwell. It's one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:44.950 --> 00:11:48.520
way of thinking about that: we're stripping&nbsp;
away all multiplicities and just considering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:54.190
all things that actually occur. So, in&nbsp;
this story, what's occurring is (-2, -1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:54.190 --> 00:12:00.730
which is that first one there, and here that&nbsp;
would be up here—let's draw a little square&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:10.870
there—that one's appearing. Then we had (-1,&nbsp;
2)—that was this one here—now it's occurring.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:22.090
And then this one over here—that one's occurring,&nbsp;
that's the (0, 3). And we also had this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.090 --> 00:12:29.275
that's (0, -1)—that was occurring three times,&nbsp;
so we'll record it. And there was also the (1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:29.275 --> 00:12:36.280
1), which is down here, and&nbsp;
the (2, 1), which is down here.

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:44.710
Okay, so if I actually sort of&nbsp;
really make this a bit clearer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:44.710 --> 00:12:53.860
so we can represent the set of pixels that occur&nbsp;
by just recording the non-zero multiplicities,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.860 --> 00:13:00.040
and we could call that F of M, short&nbsp;
for frame. So in the previous video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:09.040
I talked about sets of pixels as being frames.&nbsp;
So this multiset has this as its frame,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:09.040 --> 00:13:17.110
and another notation that I introduced is&nbsp;
that the support of the maxwell is this frame.

00:13:17.110 --> 00:13:24.790
So, we're proposing a very big change here&nbsp;
because matrix operations, matrix multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:30.370
and algebra are just workhorses of modern&nbsp;
mathematics. Someone like me, a professional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.370 --> 00:13:35.800
mathematician, will have done thousands and&nbsp;
thousands of matrix calculations in my career,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:42.130
and even undergraduate students will do dozens&nbsp;
if not hundreds of matrix calculations. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:42.130 --> 00:13:47.440
it's a big shift to start thinking, first of&nbsp;
all, of matrices not just contained in little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:54.040
rectangular boxes but sort of spread out. And&nbsp;
also, even more perhaps novel, the idea that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.040 --> 00:14:03.730
the extent of these boxes can range also over&nbsp;
integer indices. So, it's a big shift going from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.730 --> 00:14:10.840
this corner screen point of view that we started&nbsp;
with to now this full integer screen point of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:19.690
view towards maxwells. It's a big shift, and it&nbsp;
certainly requires some conceptual adjustment.

00:14:19.690 --> 00:14:25.360
And I'd like to just point out that this kind&nbsp;
of thing has some precedent. If we go back&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:30.610
three or four hundred years to Descartes'&nbsp;
time, where Cartesian coordinate geometry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.610 --> 00:14:38.500
was really first introduced, Descartes was&nbsp;
very reluctant to think about geometry on an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:44.650
entire plane in the coordinate sense. He much&nbsp;
preferred to think in terms of quadrants. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:50.260
he would divide the plane up into four quadrants&nbsp;
and say this positive quadrant—that one is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:57.850
comfortable because he can label the indices with&nbsp;
positive numbers. So, back in Descartes' day,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.850 --> 00:15:04.690
negative numbers were viewed with some suspicion.&nbsp;
Yes, one could see that they were useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:04.690 --> 00:15:12.280
for certain things, especially describing&nbsp;
debts, but their geometrical significance,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:17.140
their essential mathematical significance,&nbsp;
was not entirely so familiar as it is today.

00:15:17.140 --> 00:15:25.000
So, what we're really doing is, I suppose,&nbsp;
proposing an algebraic analog of going from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:32.620
this geometrical story to the more familiar&nbsp;
full-plane story of modern Cartesian geometry—an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.620 --> 00:15:42.190
analog of that in the algebraic setting in terms&nbsp;
of studying matrices and linear algebra. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:42.190 --> 00:15:47.230
of course, now we want to do algebra with these&nbsp;
more general kinds of matrices or maxwells,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:51.580
and the operations are the basic&nbsp;
ones of addition and multiplication.

00:15:51.580 --> 00:15:58.570
Addition is relatively straightforward because&nbsp;
addition is really component-wise—we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:05.920
just adding multisets. And in the screen&nbsp;
representation, that just corresponds to adding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:05.920 --> 00:16:13.630
multiplicities at every single pixel position. So,&nbsp;
if we want to add this maxwell with this maxwell,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:13.630 --> 00:16:19.300
we're going to get this maxwell, which is just&nbsp;
the sum of all the various multiplicities in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:26.080
each position. And of course, it's important&nbsp;
that we keep the positions coherent so that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:26.080 --> 00:16:29.830
recognize this is the (0, 0) position, this&nbsp;
is the (0, 0) position, and here is the (0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.830 --> 00:16:35.800
0) position here. So, this entry plus this entry&nbsp;
has to be this entry. Correspondingly, this 3 plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:43.240
this 1 gives us this 4, this 1 plus 0 gives us&nbsp;
1, this 0, which is implicit there but we haven't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:49.870
written it down, plus this 5 gives us 5. And&nbsp;
similarly, we get a 1 here, and a 2 plus 1 is 3.

00:16:49.870 --> 00:16:56.320
So, addition is very straightforward—it's really&nbsp;
the same kind of story. And multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.320 --> 00:17:00.880
in some sense, is also straightforward because&nbsp;
it's exactly the same definition as we had before.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:09.295
Here is our fundamental multiplication&nbsp;
of pixels: pixel (k, l) times pixel (m,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:09.295 --> 00:17:19.420
n) gives us either the pixel (k, n) in case&nbsp;
l equals m, or otherwise it gives us nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:29.770
represented by a real nothing—no zero, no dot,&nbsp;
no symbol, just emptiness. That's crucial for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:29.770 --> 00:17:35.230
us when we're working with multisets: to be able&nbsp;
to multiply this object and this object and get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:44.070
nothing that we're going to put in the resulting&nbsp;
multiset. So, this story crucially involves the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:50.310
distinguished use of nothing in this somewhat&nbsp;
novel setting and sense that we're proposing.

00:17:50.310 --> 00:17:57.240
So, let's have a look at an example of&nbsp;
maxwell multiplication. Here is a maxwell,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.240 --> 00:18:05.970
M, and here is maxwell, N. We want to multiply&nbsp;
them. So, the definition of multiplication at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:10.980
the maxwell level is just the max extension of&nbsp;
the pixel multiplication. So, we are obliged&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.980 --> 00:18:18.000
to multiply each of the pixels in the first&nbsp;
M-set, which is M, with each of the pixels in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:25.950
the second M-set, which is N. For example, we have&nbsp;
to multiply this pixel first with this one. Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.950 --> 00:18:29.850
in order to do that, we have to look at the&nbsp;
second entry here, the first entry here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:35.460
and ask: are they the same? They are not the same&nbsp;
because 1 and -1 are different, so the product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:35.460 --> 00:18:42.540
of this pixel with this pixel is empty, and it&nbsp;
contributes nothing to the final product. So here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:48.420
we get nothing, here we get nothing, here we&nbsp;
get nothing, nothing. But this product here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:48.420 --> 00:18:56.010
we get something because that 1 and that 1 agree,&nbsp;
and so the product is going to be (-2, 4), okay?

00:18:56.010 --> 00:19:00.540
Then we move to the next pixel and do the&nbsp;
same thing—well, it's exactly the same as the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.540 --> 00:19:05.190
previous one, so we're going to get another&nbsp;
(-2, 4). When we move to this one (1, -1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:05.190 --> 00:19:10.920
we look through here—how many of them agree in&nbsp;
their first entry with the second entry here? So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:15.195
we look for a -1 again, and we see&nbsp;
there's two of them, and so we get a (1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:15.195 --> 00:19:21.810
2) in this product here, and another (1, 2)&nbsp;
from this product here. And then finally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:21.810 --> 00:19:26.160
this pixel times all of these, and we're&nbsp;
only going to get something when we multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:34.980
this one with this one because those ones&nbsp;
agree, and we will get the result of (0, 4).

00:19:34.980 --> 00:19:40.980
This is what it looks like at the M-set level,&nbsp;
but most of the time, we'll probably be working&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:40.980 --> 00:19:49.800
in this screen kind of representation. So, here&nbsp;
is the maxwell represented on our screen—there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.800 --> 00:20:01.680
a (-2, 1) twice, there's a (1, -1), (1, -1) right&nbsp;
there, and there's a (0, 1) over there. And the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:07.950
second one is (-1, 2)—so (-1) in this direction,&nbsp;
(2) in this direction, and there's a 2 down,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:14.820
there's a 2 there. Then there's (0, 1) twice—this&nbsp;
(0, 1) position two times. And there's also one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:22.680
further down and then one, two, three, four&nbsp;
over. And the final product is this thing here.

00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:31.770
Well, it may seem quite different from the matrix&nbsp;
multiplication that you're used to, but in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:31.770 --> 00:20:37.200
it's not really so different. We'll see this a&nbsp;
little more next time. Here's a way of thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.200 --> 00:20:43.500
about it that maybe makes it a little bit clearer:&nbsp;
suppose we fill in this thing to make it a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:43.500 --> 00:20:52.440
bit more like a rectangular array, save that one&nbsp;
there, and let's do the same thing over here.

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:05.460
And we'll fill up also some zeros here.

00:21:05.460 --> 00:21:18.870
So what one can do is think about having arrays,&nbsp;
and actually, it's best to go over one more so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:18.870 --> 00:21:24.600
that we're in a diagonal situation—then&nbsp;
we get a better correspondence with the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:34.620
usual matrix multiplication. So, let's go&nbsp;
over there—I've now gone over to the (-2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.620 --> 00:21:43.350
-2) entry on the top. Then, if I kind of put a&nbsp;
border here and a border here and a border here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:43.350 --> 00:21:51.630
then you can convince yourself that&nbsp;
this product here is this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:51.630 --> 00:21:59.340
in the sense of just doing sort of ordinary&nbsp;
matrix multiplication on these traditional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:59.340 --> 00:22:08.130
bordered maxwells. So, for example, this&nbsp;
entry here is the result of taking this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:14.250
row here and this column here and going&nbsp;
(0, 0, 0, 2)—that's how we get that one.

00:22:14.250 --> 00:22:21.120
You don't have to do this, but if you&nbsp;
want to connect a little more directly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:27.180
with your intuition about ordinary matrix&nbsp;
multiplication, this is one way of proceeding.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:33.210
We'll have a look at this kind of thing&nbsp;
in a little bit more generality next time.

00:22:33.210 --> 00:22:38.640
So here's a little exercise for you, finally,&nbsp;
to practice a bit of matrix multiplication:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:38.640 --> 00:22:43.740
suppose that M is this particular maxwell—it's&nbsp;
a bit symmetrical—and here's another one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:48.390
also symmetrical, called N.&nbsp;
Have some fun finding powers:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:48.390 --> 00:22:53.670
M to the k, N to the k for various&nbsp;
powers for these two maxwells.

00:22:53.670 --> 00:23:01.620
In our next video, we want to understand this&nbsp;
algebra a little bit better. We want to connect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:06.840
this new kind of maxwell theory with the previous&nbsp;
one that we had—the more limited one where we were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:06.840 --> 00:23:12.180
just talking about maxwells from natural numbers.&nbsp;
We'll see that many of the same concepts apply and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:12.800 --> 00:23:15.680
have a very rich algebraic&nbsp;
structure, and in some ways,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:15.680 --> 00:23:21.230
a more symmetrical and aesthetically&nbsp;
pleasing one than we had before. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:21.230 --> 00:23:25.880
really new and exciting directions for&nbsp;
matrix theory and, in fact, linear algebra.

00:23:25.880 --> 00:23:30.050
I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

